[The US national rate of reported primary and secondary (P&S) syphilis cases, which reached a historic low in 2000 and 2001, increased almost every year since (https://www.cdc.gov/std/stats15/syphilis.htm). Men account for the most cases of P&S syphilis, with the vast majority of those cases occurring among men who have sex with men (MSM) (https://www.cdc.gov/std/syphilis/stats.htm). However, during 2013-2015, the rate increased among women, as well as men. It would be important to know the characteristics of the sexually transmitted disease outbreak on the California State Fullerton campus. More information in this regard would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources.

California State University, Fullerton (also known as Cal State Fullerton) is a public research university located in Fullerton, California. With a total enrollment of about 34 462 undergraduates and approximately 5773 graduate students, Cal State Fullerton has the largest student body out of the 23-campus California State University system (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_State_University,_Fullerton). Cal State Fullerton is designated both as a Hispanic-serving institution and an Asian American Native American Pacific Islander serving institution.

The state of California can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4949859,7131. A county map can be seen at http://www.mapsofworld.com/usa/states/california/california-county-map.html. - Mod.ML]
